#compdef constellation
# ============================================================================
# constellation - Pluggable authoritative DNS server (Rust, MPL-2.0)
#
# Author : Valerian Saliou
# Upstream: https://github.com/valeriansaliou/constellation
# crates : constellation-server (binary: constellation)
#
# Constellation is an authoritative DNS server with a managed
# HTTP REST API for dynamic record management - the use case is
# operating an internal DNS zone where records are programmatically
# added/removed (per-tenant subdomains, per-deployment GeoDNS,
# Anycast routing, autoscaling-aware A/AAAA records). The server
# is built around a Redis-backed record store + a per-zone
# pluggable flatten step that resolves CNAMEs into A/AAAA at
# write time + a per-record health check that masks unhealthy
# upstreams from the answer.
#
# Architecture: tokio runtime + actix-web for the HTTP API,
# hickory-server for the DNS protocol layer, Redis (via
# bb8-redis) as the persistent backing store, MaxMind GeoLite2
# database for IP-to-country mapping that drives GeoDNS
# routing. Operational features:
#   - GeoDNS: return different IPs per client country
#   - Health checks: skip degraded upstreams in DNS answers
#   - Flatten: replace CNAMEs with their resolved A/AAAA at
#     write time so the per-query latency stays under 1ms
#   - HTTP API: add / remove / list records via REST + JSON
#
# Flags (clap 4.x - hand-built via Command::new):
#   -c, --config <file>   - configuration file path
#                           (default ./config.cfg)
#   -V, --version         - print version (clap default)
#   -h, --help            - print help (clap default)
#
# The hickory-server lane is built on `hickory-server = "0.24"`
# + `hickory-proto = "0.24"` + `hickory-resolver = "0.24"`
# (declared verbatim at upstream Cargo.toml HEAD), the
# canonical Rust DNS implementation by Benjamin Fry + the
# hickory-dns org (github.com/hickory-dns/hickory-dns, 4400+
# stars). Hickory is the modern fork of trust-dns (the project
# was renamed in 2023 after trademark concerns); the codebase
# is the same. The library family covers the full DNS spec:
# RFC 1035 (DNS protocol), RFC 2535 (DNSSEC), RFC 7858 (DoT),
# RFC 8484 (DoH), RFC 9230 (DoQ over QUIC) - the only Rust
# DNS implementation with a credible claim to full coverage.
# constellation uses hickory-server to drive the actual DNS
# wire-protocol handler that fronts the Redis-backed record
# store.
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AXIS 228 :: DNS server libraries (RFC 1035 + DoH/DoT/DoQ)  [OPENS]
# Round 1382 :: Rust slot 1 of 4 :: OPENS Axis 228
#
# Cross-language canonical library family for this axis (proposed):
#   Rust    : hickory-dns/hickory-server   - full DNS protocol stack
#                                            (formerly trust-dns)
#   Go      : miekg/dns                    - de-facto Go DNS library
#                                            (powers CoreDNS, Cilium,
#                                             Hashicorp Consul, Tailscale)
#   TS/Node : mafintosh/dns-packet         - low-level DNS packet
#                                            codec (companion: multicast-dns,
#                                             dns-rcode-helper, ...)
#
# DNS server libraries are a tightly bound axis: every modern
# Go DNS-related project imports miekg/dns - CoreDNS, Cilium's
# network policies, Consul's service discovery, Tailscale's
# MagicDNS, Pi-hole's FTL daemon (Go rewrite), Wireguard's
# wg-friendlier resolvers. There is no second contender; the
# library has zero serious alternatives in Go because miekg
# implemented the entire DNS spec corpus in ~2010 and has
# maintained byte-for-byte spec conformance ever since.
#
# Hickory occupies the same position in Rust but had to live
# under the original trust-dns name from 2014-2023. The
# rename was friction-only - the library was canonical the
# entire time. dns-packet in the JS world is more low-level
# than the other two slots: it's a packet encoder/decoder,
# not a server framework, so any JS DNS server (dns2, denoland/
# deno_std/dns, ...) builds on top of dns-packet for the
# wire layer.
#
# Cross-language interop for DNS is total at the wire level
# (RFC 1035 is a byte-precise protocol). What diverges across
# the axes is the *abstraction model* of the library: hickory
# wraps DNS in a typed Request/Response trait, miekg/dns
# exposes raw Msg structs + chained Handler interface, dns-
# packet exposes a Buffer-in/Buffer-out codec function.
# ============================================================================

_constellation() {
    local context state state_descr line
    typeset -A opt_args

    _arguments -s -S \
        '(-c --config)'{-c,--config}'[path to configuration file (default ./config.cfg)]:file:_files -g "*.(cfg|toml)"' \
        '(- *)'{-V,--version}'[print version]' \
        '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[print help]'
}

_constellation "$@"
